{"title_page": "Kedar Nath Neupane", "text_new": "[[File:Kanya mandir high school.jpg|thumb|Kanya Mandir High School, Kathmandu]]\n'''Kedar Nath Neupane''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u0915\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0930\u0928\u093e\u0925 \u0928\u094d\u092f\u094c\u092a\u093e\u0928\u0947) (29 November 1927 - 13 October 1971) was a Nepalese educator and author. He was one of the founders and headmaster of Kanya Mandir High School at Nhyokha, [[Kathmandu]].\n\nNeupane was born in Kathmandu to father Damodar Nath and mother Sumitra Neupane. He held [[Master of Arts]] (MA) and [[Bachelor of Education]] (BEd) degrees, and worked as a teacher. He was a champion of teaching [[Nepal Bhasa]] as a subject in school even though it was not his mother tongue, and played a central role in having it included in the curriculum of Kanya Mandir High School.\n\nIn 1969, Neupane was named an advisor to the National Educational Advisory Board.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |title= Nepal Press Report, Issues 200-299 |url= https://books.google.com.np/books?id=erUjAQAAMAAJ&q=kedar+nath+neupane+kanya+mandir&dq=kedar+nath+neupane+kanya+mandir&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xrP4UaicDoH7rAeAnIGwCg&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA |accessdate=31 July 2013 |year=1969 |publisher= Regmi Research Project |location= Kathmandu |isbn= |page=2}}</ref> He has also served as secretary of Chwas\u0101 P\u0101s\u0101, a Nepal Bhasa literary organization, and worked to promote it along with cultural expert Satya Mohan Joshi and litterateurs [[Kedar Man Byathit]] and Dhunswa Sayami.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nepal Sambat will have no adverse impact |url=http://www.gorkhapatra.org.np/gopa.detail.php?article_id=9026&cat_id=29 |accessdate=8 August 2013 |newspaper=The Rising Nepal |year=2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808053114/http://www.gorkhapatra.org.np/gopa.detail.php?article_id=9026&cat_id=29 |archivedate= 8 August 2014 }}</ref>\n\nNeupane wrote in [[Nepali language|Nepali]] and Nepal Bhasa. He has published a book entitled ''Kehenyata Pati'' (\u0915\u0947\u0939\u0947\u0901\u092f\u093e\u0924 \u092a\u0924\u093f) (\"Letter to Younger Sister\") in Nepal Bhasa. It appeared in 1952.<ref>{{cite book |last= Bajracharya |first= Phanindra Ratna |title= Who's Who in Nepal Bhasha |url= |accessdate= |year=2003 |publisher= Nepal Bhasa Academy |location= Kathmandu |isbn=99933-560-0-X |page=85}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neupane, Kedar Nath}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Nepalese educators]]\n[[Category:Nepal Bhasa writers]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male writers]]\n[[Category:Nepali-language writers]]\n\n\n{{Nepal-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kanya mandir high school.jpg|thumb|Kanya Mandir High School, Kathmandu]]\n'''Kedar Nath Neupane''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u0915\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0930\u0928\u093e\u0925 \u0928\u094d\u092f\u094c\u092a\u093e\u0928\u0947) (29 November 1927 - 13 October 1971) was a Nepalese educator and author. He was one of the founders and headmaster of Kanya Mandir High School at Nhyokha, [[Kathmandu]].\n\nNeupane was born in Kathmandu to father Damodar Nath and mother Sumitra Neupane. He held [[Master of Arts]] (MA) and [[Bachelor of Education]] (BEd) degrees, and worked as a teacher. He was a champion of teaching [[Nepal Bhasa]] as a subject in school even though it was not his mother tongue, and played a central role in having it included in the curriculum of Kanya Mandir High School. \n\nIn 1969, Neupane was named an advisor to the National Educational Advisory Board.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |title= Nepal Press Report, Issues 200-299 |url= https://books.google.com.np/books?id=erUjAQAAMAAJ&q=kedar+nath+neupane+kanya+mandir&dq=kedar+nath+neupane+kanya+mandir&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xrP4UaicDoH7rAeAnIGwCg&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA |accessdate=31 July 2013 |year=1969 |publisher= Regmi Research Project |location= Kathmandu |isbn= |page=2}}</ref> He has also served as secretary of Chwas\u0101 P\u0101s\u0101, a Nepal Bhasa literary organization, and worked to promote it along with cultural expert Satya Mohan Joshi and litterateurs [[Kedar Man Byathit]] and Dhunswa Sayami.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nepal Sambat will have no adverse impact |url=http://www.gorkhapatra.org.np/gopa.detail.php?article_id=9026&cat_id=29 |accessdate=8 August 2013 |newspaper=The Rising Nepal |year=2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808053114/http://www.gorkhapatra.org.np/gopa.detail.php?article_id=9026&cat_id=29 |archivedate= 8 August 2014 }}</ref>\n\nNeupane wrote in [[Nepali language|Nepali]] and Nepal Bhasa. He has published a book entitled ''Kehenyata Pati'' (\u0915\u0947\u0939\u0947\u0901\u092f\u093e\u0924 \u092a\u0924\u093f) (\"Letter to Younger Sister\") in Nepal Bhasa. It appeared in 1952.<ref>{{cite book |last= Bajracharya |first= Phanindra Ratna |title= Who's Who in Nepal Bhasha |url= |accessdate= |year=2003 |publisher= Nepal Bhasa Academy |location= Kathmandu |isbn=99933-560-0-X |page=85}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neupane, Kedar Nath}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Nepalese educators]]\n[[Category:Nepal Bhasa writers]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male writers]]\n[[Category:Nepali-language writers]]\n\n\n{{Nepal-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kedar_Nath_Neupane"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alaska", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Alaska, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alaska\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Alaska]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n| arrival_date    = March 07, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| type            = \n| confirmed_cases = 285\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 98\n| deaths          = 9\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://coronavirus.alaska.gov/}}\n| hospitalized_cases = 32\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Alaska]] on March 12, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska's coronavirus response has escalated as the number of cases has grown. Here's where things stand. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/22/alaskas-coronavirus-response-has-escalated-as-the-number-of-cases-has-grown-heres-where-things-stand/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]]'s office declared a state of emergency to ensure all entities have the necessary response resources.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/11/governor-issues-public-health-disaster-emergency-declaration-for-covid-19/|title=Governor Issues Public Health Disaster Emergency Declaration for COVID-19|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The next day, the first case, a foreign national in [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], was announced to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/12/first-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-by-alaska-state-public-health-laboratory-is-an-international-resident/|title=First case of COVID-19 confirmed by Alaska State Public Health Laboratory is an international resident|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Alaska medical cases chart}}\n[[File:Ketchikan, Alaska, Estados Unidos, 2017-08-16, DD 01.jpg|thumb|Ketchikan, one of the places affected by COVID-19 during the 2020 outbreak in Alaska]]\nIn March 21, 2020, [[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]], a small, coastal town of approximately 8,000 residents located in [[Southeast Alaska]] was determined to have a cluster of six COVID-19 cases. The town [[shelter in place|sheltered in place]] for the following 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |first=Eric |last=Stone |title=Officials announce three more COVID-19 cases in Ketchikan |url=https://www.ktoo.org/2020/03/21/ketchikan-officials-announce-three-more-covid-19-cases/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[KRBD]] via [[KTOO-TV]]|date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On March 24, 2020, three more cases of COVID-19 were found in Ketchikan, bringing the total there to nine.<ref>{{cite news |title=UPDATE: Ketchikan confirms 3 new cases of COVID-19 |url=https://www.ktuu.com/content/news/Ketchikan-confirms-2-new--confirmed-cases-of-COVID-19-569066131.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[KTUU-TV]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The next day, the total cases there reached 11.<ref>{{cite web|first=Eric|last=Stone|url=https://www.krbd.org/2020/03/25/two-new-coronavirus-cases-bring-ketchikans-total-to-11/ |title=Two new coronavirus cases bring Ketchikan's total to 11 |date=26 March 2020|publisher=[[KRBD]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020, the number of positive cases of COVID-19 in Ketchikan rose to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kinyradio.com/news/news-of-the-north/ketchikan-covid-19-cases-rise-to-14-after-new-diagnosis/ |title=Ketchikan COVID-19 cases rise to 14 after new diagnosis |date=April 1, 2020|publisher=[[KINY]]|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Measures==\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]] ordered public schools to close from March 16 to 30,<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska officials close public schools to students through March 30 to limit spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/14/alaska-officials-close-k-12-public-schools-to-students-for-extra-2-weeks-to-limit-spread-of-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\">{{cite news |title=Alaska's statewide school closure is beginning. No one knows quite how it will work. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/education/2020/03/16/alaskas-statewide-school-closure-is-about-to-begin-no-one-knows-quite-how-it-will-work/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> which was later extended to May 1.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\">{{cite news |last1=Hanlon |first1=Tegan |last2=Ruskin |first2=Liz |last3=Media |first3=Alaska Public |title=State extends Alaska school closures as coronavirus count grows to 14 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/20/state-announces-new-business-closures-for-fairbanks-ketchikan-and-asks-alaskans-to-stop-all-non-essential-travel/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> School districts were advised to find ways to use remote learning, but there was concern about the impact on the youngest students, special ed students, and small and remote areas where online learning is more difficult.<ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\"/>\n\nOn March 17, Governor Dunleavy announced the creation of the Alaska Economic Stabilization Team (AEST).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/home/covid-19-economy/|title=COVID-19 Alaska Economic Stabilization Team \u2013 Mike Dunleavy|website=gov.alaska.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nEffective March 18, restaurants were restricted to take-out and delivery, and entertainment venues such as movie theaters and gyms were closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruskin |first1=Liz |title=State bans restaurant dining as Alaska's confirmed coronavirus cases grow to 6 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/17/state-bans-restaurant-dining-as-alaskas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-6/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Mayor of Anchorage]] [[Ethan Berkowitz]] issued an \"emergency hunker down order\" effective March 22.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some businesses were closed in [[Fairbanks North Star Borough]] and [[Ketchikan Gateway Borough]].<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some villages restricted air travel.<ref name=\"villages 1\">{{cite news |title=Alaska villages to ban, restrict air travel amid coronavirus |url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/Alaska-villages-to-ban-restrict-air-travel-amid-15148159.php |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Hour |date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"villages 2\">{{cite news |title=Alaska rural villages begin to ban or severely restrict air travel in hopes of slowing coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/rural-alaska/2020/03/20/alaska-rural-villages-begin-to-ban-or-severely-restrict-air-travel-in-hopes-of-slowing-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Mike Dunleavy ordered everyone arriving in Alaska to self-quarantine for 14 days upon arrival, effective March 25, with limited exceptions.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Health Mandate |url=https://gov.alaska.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/03232020-SOA-COVID-19-Health-Mandate-010.pdf |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |last2=Bosman |first2=Julie |last3=Bogel-Burroughs |first3=Nicholas |title=Governors Tell Outsiders From 'Hot Zone' to Stay Away as Virus Divides States |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/us/coronavirus-united-states.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Remote communities ==\nBy March 22, some remote villages were attempting to isolate themselves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/remote-alaska-villages-isolate-themselves-further-in-effort-to-shield-against-coronavirus|title=Remote Alaska Villages Isolate Themselves Further in Effort to Shield Against Coronavirus|last=Hopkins|first=Kyle|date=2020-03-22|website=ProPublica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn the event of a COVID-19 case being identified in a remote community, the state plan is to transport the patient to a hub city for treatment rather than dispatching medical workers to the remote area.<ref name=\"villages 1\" /><ref name=\"villages 2\" />\n\n== Statistics ==\n[[File:Alaska-cases-map (9).png|thumb|March 2020 map of confirmed COVID-19 cases in Alaska]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Alaska<ref name=\"ADHSS\">{{cite web|url= http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/monitoring.aspx |title=Case Counts|publisher=Alaska Department of Health|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\nUpdated April 13, 2020 \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Community\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchor Point, Alaska|Anchor Point]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n|123\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bethel, Alaska|Bethel]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Chugiak, Anchorage|Chugiak]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Craig, Alaska|Craig]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Delta Junction, Alaska|Delta Junction]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Eagle River, Anchorage|Eagle River]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Fairbanks, Alaska|Fairbanks]]\n|63\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Girdwood, Anchorage, Alaska|Girdwood]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Homer, Alaska|Homer]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Interior - other\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Juneau, Alaska|Juneau]]\n|18\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kenai, Alaska|Kenai]]\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]]\n|15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[North Pole, Alaska|North Pole]]\n|15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Palmer, Alaska|Palmer]]\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Petersburg, Alaska|Petersburg]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Seward, Alaska|Seward]]\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Soldotna, Alaska|Soldotna]]\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sterling, Alaska|Sterling]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Yukon\u2013Koyukuk Census Area, Alaska|Yukon-Koyukuk Census Area]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wasilla, Alaska|Wasilla]]\n|9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |'''Total'''\n|'''285'''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Age ranges===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+{{nowrap|Alaska COVID-19 cases by age group}}\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\" | Age\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Cases\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Number\n! scope=\"col\" |Deaths\n|-\n! 80+\n|6\n|0\n|-\n! 70\u201379\n|19\n|5\n|-\n! 60\u201369\n|40\n|1\n|-\n! 50\u201359\n|55\n|1\n|-\n! 40\u201349\n|44\n|0\n|-\n! 30\u201339\n|56\n|1\n|-\n! 20\u201329\n|38\n|0\n|-\n! 10\u201319\n|14\n|0\n|-\n! 0\u20139\n|5\n|0\n|-\n! Total\n|'''277'''\n|'''8'''\n|}\n'''Source:''' ADHSS, April 13, 2020.<ref name=\"ADHSS\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/default.aspx Coronavirus information] from [[Alaska Department of Health and Social Services]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|United States|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Alaska]]\n[[Category:2020 in Alaska|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Health in Alaska]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Alaska, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alaska\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Alaska]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n| arrival_date    = March 07, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| type            = \n| confirmed_cases = 285\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 98\n| deaths          = 9\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://coronavirus.alaska.gov/}}\n| hospitalized_cases = 32\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Alaska]] on March 12, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska's coronavirus response has escalated as the number of cases has grown. Here's where things stand. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/22/alaskas-coronavirus-response-has-escalated-as-the-number-of-cases-has-grown-heres-where-things-stand/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]]'s office declared a state of emergency to ensure all entities have the necessary response resources.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/11/governor-issues-public-health-disaster-emergency-declaration-for-covid-19/|title=Governor Issues Public Health Disaster Emergency Declaration for COVID-19|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The next day, the first case, a foreign national in [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], was announced to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/12/first-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-by-alaska-state-public-health-laboratory-is-an-international-resident/|title=First case of COVID-19 confirmed by Alaska State Public Health Laboratory is an international resident|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Alaska medical cases chart}}\n[[File:Ketchikan, Alaska, Estados Unidos, 2017-08-16, DD 01.jpg|thumb|Ketchikan, one of the places affected by COVID-19 during the 2020 outbreak in Alaska]]\nIn March 21, 2020, [[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]], a small, coastal town of approximately 8,000 residents located in [[Southeast Alaska]] was determined to have a cluster of six COVID-19 cases. The town [[shelter in place|sheltered in place]] for the following 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |first=Eric |last=Stone |title=Officials announce three more COVID-19 cases in Ketchikan |url=https://www.ktoo.org/2020/03/21/ketchikan-officials-announce-three-more-covid-19-cases/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[KRBD]] via [[KTOO-TV]]|date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On March 24, 2020, three more cases of COVID-19 were found in Ketchikan, bringing the total there to nine.<ref>{{cite news |title=UPDATE: Ketchikan confirms 3 new cases of COVID-19 |url=https://www.ktuu.com/content/news/Ketchikan-confirms-2-new--confirmed-cases-of-COVID-19-569066131.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[KTUU-TV]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The next day, the total cases there reached 11.<ref>{{cite web|first=Eric|last=Stone|url=https://www.krbd.org/2020/03/25/two-new-coronavirus-cases-bring-ketchikans-total-to-11/ |title=Two new coronavirus cases bring Ketchikan's total to 11 |date=26 March 2020|publisher=[[KRBD]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020, the number of positive cases of COVID-19 in Ketchikan rose to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kinyradio.com/news/news-of-the-north/ketchikan-covid-19-cases-rise-to-14-after-new-diagnosis/ |title=Ketchikan COVID-19 cases rise to 14 after new diagnosis |date=April 1, 2020|publisher=[[KINY]]|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Measures==\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]] ordered public schools to close from March 16 to 30,<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska officials close public schools to students through March 30 to limit spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/14/alaska-officials-close-k-12-public-schools-to-students-for-extra-2-weeks-to-limit-spread-of-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\">{{cite news |title=Alaska's statewide school closure is beginning. No one knows quite how it will work. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/education/2020/03/16/alaskas-statewide-school-closure-is-about-to-begin-no-one-knows-quite-how-it-will-work/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> which was later extended to May 1.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\">{{cite news |last1=Hanlon |first1=Tegan |last2=Ruskin |first2=Liz |last3=Media |first3=Alaska Public |title=State extends Alaska school closures as coronavirus count grows to 14 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/20/state-announces-new-business-closures-for-fairbanks-ketchikan-and-asks-alaskans-to-stop-all-non-essential-travel/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> School districts were advised to find ways to use remote learning, but there was concern about the impact on the youngest students, special ed students, and small and remote areas where online learning is more difficult.<ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\"/>\n\nOn March 17, Governor Dunleavy announced the creation of the Alaska Economic Stabilization Team (AEST).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/home/covid-19-economy/|title=COVID-19 Alaska Economic Stabilization Team \u2013 Mike Dunleavy|website=gov.alaska.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nEffective March 18, restaurants were restricted to take-out and delivery, and entertainment venues such as movie theaters and gyms were closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruskin |first1=Liz |title=State bans restaurant dining as Alaska's confirmed coronavirus cases grow to 6 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/17/state-bans-restaurant-dining-as-alaskas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-6/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Mayor of Anchorage]] [[Ethan Berkowitz]] issued an \"emergency hunker down order\" effective March 22.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some businesses were closed in [[Fairbanks North Star Borough]] and [[Ketchikan Gateway Borough]].<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some villages restricted air travel.<ref name=\"villages 1\">{{cite news |title=Alaska villages to ban, restrict air travel amid coronavirus |url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/Alaska-villages-to-ban-restrict-air-travel-amid-15148159.php |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Hour |date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"villages 2\">{{cite news |title=Alaska rural villages begin to ban or severely restrict air travel in hopes of slowing coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/rural-alaska/2020/03/20/alaska-rural-villages-begin-to-ban-or-severely-restrict-air-travel-in-hopes-of-slowing-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Mike Dunleavy ordered everyone arriving in Alaska to self-quarantine for 14 days upon arrival, effective March 25, with limited exceptions.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Health Mandate |url=https://gov.alaska.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/03232020-SOA-COVID-19-Health-Mandate-010.pdf |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |last2=Bosman |first2=Julie |last3=Bogel-Burroughs |first3=Nicholas |title=Governors Tell Outsiders From 'Hot Zone' to Stay Away as Virus Divides States |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/us/coronavirus-united-states.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Remote communities ==\nBy March 22, some remote villages were attempting to isolate themselves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/remote-alaska-villages-isolate-themselves-further-in-effort-to-shield-against-coronavirus|title=Remote Alaska Villages Isolate Themselves Further in Effort to Shield Against Coronavirus|last=Hopkins|first=Kyle|date=2020-03-22|website=ProPublica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn the event of a COVID-19 case being identified in a remote community, the state plan is to transport the patient to a hub city for treatment rather than dispatching medical workers to the remote area.<ref name=\"villages 1\" /><ref name=\"villages 2\" />\n\n== Statistics ==\n[[File:Alaska-cases-map (9).png|thumb|March 2020 map of confirmed COVID-19 cases in Alaska]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Alaska<ref name=\"ADHSS\">{{cite web|url= http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/monitoring.aspx |title=Case Counts|publisher=Alaska Department of Health|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\nUpdated April 13, 2020 \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Community\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchor Point, Alaska|Anchor Point]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n|123\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bethel, Alaska|Bethel]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Chugiak, Anchorage|Chugiak]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Craig, Alaska|Craig]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Delta Junction, Alaska|Delta Junction]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Eagle River, Anchorage|Eagle River]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Fairbanks, Alaska|Fairbanks]]\n|63\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Girdwood, Anchorage, Alaska|Girdwood]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Homer, Alaska|Homer]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" Interior - other\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Juneau, Alaska|Juneau]]\n|18\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kenai, Alaska|Kenai]]\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]]\n|15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[North Pole, Alaska|North Pole]]\n|15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Palmer, Alaska|Palmer]]\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Petersburg, Alaska|Petersburg]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Seward, Alaska|Seward]]\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Soldotna, Alaska|Soldotna]]\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sterling, Alaska|Sterling]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Yukon\u2013Koyukuk Census Area, Alaska|