{"title_page": "William H. Leder", "text_new": "{{short description|U.S. Navy pilot and Air Medal recipient}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name          = William H. Leder\n|image         = Ensign William Leder (bust).jpg\n|image_size    = 200px\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date |1918|5|5}}\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1943|9|5|1918|5|5}}\n|placeofburial_label =\n|birth_place   = [[Flasher, North Dakota]]\n|death_place   = [[Ellensburg, Washington]]\n|placeofburial = [[Evergreen Washelli Memorial Park]]\n|nickname      =\n|allegiance={{flag|United States of America}}\n|branch        = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears  = 1941\u20131943\n|rank          = [[Lieutenant (United States)|Lieutenant (j.g.)]]\n|unit          = [[VF-10|Fighting Squadron 10]]\n|commands      =\n|battles       =\n{{plainlist|\n*[[World War II]]\n*:[[Battle of Santa Cruz Islands]]\n}}\n|awards        =\n{{plainlist|\n*[[Air Medal|Air Medal]]\n}}\n|relations     =\n|laterwork     =\n}}\n'''William Henry Leder''' (May 5, 1918 \u2013 September 5, 1943) was a [[fighter pilot]] with the [[United States Naval Reserve]] (USNR) during [[World War II]]. He is credited with scoring multiple victories during the conflict flying a [[Grumman F4F Wildcat]]. For actions during the [[Battle of Santa Cruz Islands]] he was awarded the [[Air Medal]].<ref>{{cite web |title=William Henry Leder |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/24645703/william-henry-leder |website=Find a Grave}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nLeder was born in [[Flasher, North Dakota]] in 1918, the son of Helena Augusta Wall and Carl Benjamin Leder. He attended [[Mandan High School]] in [[Mandan, North Dakota]]. After high school, he attended North Dakota State Teachers College and graduated with a B.A. Degree. He taught in public schools in North Dakota for two years before enlisting. He enlisted in the Navy on April 12, 1941.<ref>U.S. World War II Navy Muster Rolls, 1938-1949</ref>\n\n== World War II ==\n[[File:VF-10 pilots on USS Enterprise (CV-6) c1942.jpg|thumb|left|200px|VF-10 pilots on {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}} during the [[Guadalcanal Campaign]] (William H. Leder in front row on knee, far left).]] Leder was initially stationed at the [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint_Paul_Joint_Air_Reserve_Station|Naval Reserve Aviation Base]] in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]. He became an aviation cadet on October 1, 1941 and attended flight training at [[Naval Air Station Pensacola]]. He was commissioned an ensign on May 15, 1942. On May 18 of that same year, he married Kathryn Sylvia Loran<ref>Florida, County Marriage Records, 1823-1982</ref> before being transferred to Aircraft Carrier Training Group [[NAS San Diego]] in June. \n\nIn August of 1942, he joined [[VF-10|Fighting Squadron 10 (VF-10)]] before being shipped out to the [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theater]].<ref>National Archives Veterans' Service Records</ref>\n\nLeder flew as a member of what was known as the [[Cactus Air Force]]. He was part of a large assembly of allied air power assigned to the [[Solomon Islands]] in support of the [[Guadalcanal campaign]]. He was stationed on the [[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|USS ''Enterprise'']] during the [[Battle of Santa Cruz Islands]] and flew multiple air combat patrol missions in defense of his carrier group against enemy Japanese forces.\n\nIn his first air combat engagement on October 26th, 1942, he shot down at least one enemy dive bomber in defense of the ''Enterprise''. \n\nOn November 13, 1942, he was part of a four plane flight on combat patrol over the ''Enterprise'' that intercepted and shot down a Japanese bomber shadowing the task force. \n\nLater on January 30, 1943, he shot down a torpedo bomber attempting to attack the cruiser [[USS Chicago (CA-29)|USS ''Chicago'']] as it sat damaged near [[Rennell Island]].\n\n== Air Medal ==\nLeder was nominated by his commander for the Distinguished Flying Cross and was ultimately awarded the [[Air Medal]] for his actions in the Pacific.\n\n'''Citation:'''\n\n:Conspicuous courage and skill in air combat with the enemy. On October 26, 1942, while defending your carrier from air attack in the Battle of Santa Cruz Islands, you destroyed one enemy dive bomber and probably destroyed another before they could release their bombs. In November 13, 1942, while a member of the combat patrol over the U.S.S. ENTERPRISE, you assisted in shooting down one four engine patrol bomber which was attempting to shadow your task force. On January 30, 1943, while on combat patrol over the damaged cruiser USS CHICAGO in the vicinity of Rennell Island, yourself and three other pilots intercepted, by sight contact, an enemy heavily armed twin engine torpedo bomber which was preceding an enemy attack group of twelve torpedo bombers for the obvious purpose of reconnoitering our forces and directing the attack. After a running fight lasting twenty minutes and carried on at speeds approaching 300 m.p.h., you succeeded in shooting the enemy down in flames. Your courage, tenacity, and skill were exemplary and were in keeping with the highest traditions of the U.S. Naval Service.\n\n== Later career and death ==\n[[File:Bill Leder Headstone.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Memorial headstone at [[Evergreen Washelli Memorial Park]].]]\nAfter action in the Pacific, Leder moved to [[Woodinville, Washington]] and was stationed at the Ellensburg Army Airfield (today [[Bowers Airport|Bowers Field]]) in [[Ellensburg, Washington]] as a [[test pilot]]. On September 5th, 1943, the  Navy plane he was flying caught fire midair, and he crashed near the airfield and was killed. <ref>{{cite news |title=Navy Releases Name of Fliers In Crashes Here |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |periodical=[[Daily Record (Washington)|Ellensburg Daily Record]] |date=September 8, 1943 |page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Naval Flier Killed |periodical=[[Lewiston Morning Tribune]] |date=September 9, 1943 |page=4}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leder, William H.}}\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:United States Navy pilots of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:Aviators from North Dakota]]\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|U.S. Navy pilot and Air Medal recipient}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name          = William H. Leder\n|image         = Ensign William Leder (bust).jpg\n|image_size    = 200px\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date |1918|5|5}}\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1943|9|5|1918|5|5}}\n|placeofburial_label =\n|birth_place   = [[Flasher, North Dakota]]\n|death_place   = [[Ellensburg, Washington]]\n|placeofburial = [[Evergreen Washelli Memorial Park]]\n|nickname      =\n|allegiance={{flag|United States of America}}\n|branch        = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears  = 1941\u20131943\n|rank          = [[Lieutenant (United States)|Lieutenant (j.g.)]]\n|unit          = [[VF-10|Fighting Squadron 10]]\n|commands      =\n|battles       =\n{{plainlist|\n*[[World War II]]\n*:[[Battle of Santa Cruz Islands]]\n}}\n|awards        =\n{{plainlist|\n*[[Air Medal|Air Medal]]\n}}\n|relations     =\n|laterwork     =\n}}\n'''William Henry Leder''' (May 5, 1918 \u2013 September 5, 1943) was a [[fighter pilot]] with the [[United States Naval Reserve]] (USNR) during [[World War II]]. He is credited with scoring multiple victories during the conflict flying a [[Grumman F4F Wildcat]]. For actions during the [[Battle of Santa Cruz Islands]] he was awarded the [[Air Medal]].<ref>{{cite web |title=William Henry Leder |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/24645703/william-henry-leder |website=Find a Grave}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nLeder was born in [[Flasher, North Dakota]] in 1918, the son of Helena Augusta Wall and Carl Benjamin Leder. He attended [[Mandan High School]] in [[Mandan, North Dakota]]. After high school, he attended North Dakota State Teachers College and graduated with a B.A. Degree. He taught in public schools in North Dakota for two years before enlisting. He enlisted in the Navy on April 12, 1941.<ref>U.S. World War II Navy Muster Rolls, 1938-1949</ref>\n\n== World War II ==\n[[File:VF-10 pilots on USS Enterprise (CV-6) c1942.jpg|thumb|left|200px|VF-10 pilots on {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}} during the [[Guadalcanal Campaign]] (William H. Leder in front row on knee, far left).]] Leder was initially stationed at the [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint_Paul_Joint_Air_Reserve_Station|Naval Reserve Aviation Base]] in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]. He became an aviation cadet on October 1, 1941 and attended flight training at [[Naval Air Station Pensacola]]. He was commissioned an ensign on May 15, 1942. On May 18 of that same year, he married Kathryn Sylvia Loran<ref>Florida, County Marriage Records, 1823-1982</ref> before being transferred to Aircraft Carrier Training Group [[NAS San Diego]] in June. \n\nIn August of 1942, he joined [[VF-10|Fighting Squadron 10 (VF-10)]] before being shipped out to the [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theater]].<ref>National Archives Veterans' Service Records</ref>\n\nLeder flew as a member of what was known as the [[Cactus Air Force]]. He was part of a large assembly of allied air power assigned to the [[Solomon Islands]] in support of the [[Guadalcanal campaign]]. He was stationed on the [[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|USS ''Enterprise'']] during the [[Battle of Santa Cruz Islands]] and flew multiple air combat patrol missions in defense of his carrier group against enemy Japanese forces.\n\nIn his first air combat engagement on October 26th, 1942, he shot down at least one enemy dive bomber in defense of the ''Enterprise''. \n\nOn November 13, 1942, he was part of a four plane flight on combat patrol over the ''Enterprise'' that intercepted and shot down a Japanese bomber shadowing the task force. \n\nLater on January 30, 1943, he shot down a torpedo bomber attempting to attack the cruiser [[USS Chicago (CA-29)|USS ''Chicago'']] as it sat damaged near [[Rennell Island]].\n\n== Air Medal ==\nLeder was nominated by his commander for the Distinguished Flying Cross and was ultimately awarded the [[Air Medal]] for his actions in the Pacific.\n\n'''Citation:'''\n\n:Conspicuous courage and skill in air combat with the enemy. On October 26, 1942, while defending your carrier from air attack in the Battle of Santa Cruz Islands, you destroyed one enemy dive bomber and probably destroyed another before they could release their bombs. In November 13, 1942, while a member of the combat patrol over the U.S.S. ENTERPRISE, you assisted in shooting down one four engine patrol bomber which was attempting to shadow your task force. On January 30, 1943, while on combat patrol over the damaged cruiser USS CHICAGO in the vicinity of Rennell Island, yourself and three other pilots intercepted, by sight contact, an enemy heavily armed twin engine torpedo bomber which was preceding an enemy attack group of twelve torpedo bombers for the obvious purpose of reconnoitering our forces and directing the attack. After a running fight lasting twenty minutes and carried on at speeds approaching 300 m.p.h., you succeeded in shooting the enemy down in flames. Your courage, tenacity, and skill were exemplary and were in keeping with the highest traditions of the U.S. Naval Service.\n\n== Later career and death ==\n[[File:Bill Leder Headstone.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Memorial headstone at [[Evergreen Washelli Memorial Park]].]]\nAfter action in the Pacific, Leder moved to [[Woodinville, Washington]] and was stationed at the Ellensburg Army Airfield (today [[Bowers Airport|Bowers Field]]) in [[Ellensburg, Washington]] as a [[test pilot]]. On September 5th, 1943, the  Navy plane he was flying caught fire midair, and he crashed near the airfield and was killed. <ref>{{cite news |title=Flyer is Killed in Plane Crash |publisher=[[Daily Record (Washington)|Ellensburg Daily Record]] |date=September 8, 1943}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Naval Flier Killed |work=Page 4 |publisher=[[Lewiston Morning Tribune]] |date=September 9, 1943}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leder, William H.}}\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:United States Navy pilots of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:Aviators from North Dakota]]\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Brykeller", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added proper reference to newspaper citations, added page numbers, fixed title of daily record article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_H._Leder"}
{"title_page": "Lullwater (band)", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|Music|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Lullwater\n| image           = Lullwater performing Live Left to right- Roy Beatty, John Strickland, Joe Wilson, Daniel Binnie.jpg\n| image_upright   = 1.15\n| landscape       = yes\n| alt             = Photo of Lullwater, a band from Athens, GA\n| caption         = Lullwater performing live (left to right- Roy Beatty, John Strickland, Joe Wilson, Daniel Binnie)\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[Athens, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre           = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Hard rock]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n* [[Grunge]]\n}}\n| years_active    = 2007\u2013Present\n| label           = {{Flatlist|\n* Independent Artist\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{Flatlist|\n* Enochian\n* Joe Wilson Music\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|lullwatermusic.com}}\n| current_members = \n* [[John Strickland]]\n* [[Joe Wilson]]\n* [[Roy Beatty]]\n* [[Daniel Binnie]]\n| past_members    = \n* [[Phil Bush]]\n* [[Nick Thomas]]\n* [[Brett Strickland]]\n}}\n'''Lullwater''' is a [[rock (genre)|rock]] band formed in [[Athens, Georgia]] in 2007. The music group is known for its influences in the Seattle [[Grunge]] Sound and 80's hard rock.  Formed by John Strickland (lead vocals, rhythm guitar), Lullwater also includes Roy Beatty (bass), Joseph Wilson (drums) and Daniel Binnie (guitar). The band released their debut album, \u201cLullwater\u201d, on September 17, 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screamermagazine.com/interviews/done-lullwater-athens-georgia-delivers/|title=LULLWATER - Athens, Georgia Delivers Again|date=August 27, 2014|website=Screamer Magazine}}</ref> and toured to support that album.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://betweenthenotes.blog/2014/10/23/interview-with-lullwater/|title=Interview with Lullwater|date=October 23, 2014}}</ref> The band was named from the street that their original drummer lived on in Athens.  Their band practice house was on Lullwater Road in Athens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.last.fm/music/Lullwater|title=Lullwater music, videos, stats, and photos|website=Last.fm}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===2007 \u2013 2011: Early days of the band and lineup changes===\nLullwater is brought together by John Strickland.  He completed the band's lineup by using Brett Strickland on lead guitar.  Drum duties were handled by Nick Thomas.  Phil Bush was the bass player. In 2009, Roy Beatty replaced Phil Bush as Lullwater's bass player.  In 2011, drummer Nick Thomas left the band and was replaced by Joseph Wilson from Savannah, GA, former dummer for Wormsloew.\n\n===2012 \u2013 2014: first album release===\nWith its new lineup, Lullwater began playing more clubs and touring.  In 2013, Lullwater recorded their first album at [[London Bridge Studio]] in Seattle, WA.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  Lullwater's self-titled album \u201cLullwater\u201d, released on September 17, 2013, pays homage to the grunge bands of the early 1990s who influenced their sound. The album was recorded on tape at London Bridge Studios in Seattle, WA and produced by Jonathan Plum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/noisetrade/music/lullwater|title=Lullwater Albums :: NoiseTrade :: Paste Magazine|website=www.pastemagazine.com}}</ref>  To promote \u201cLullwater\u201d, the band toured for 10 months following the release of the album, opening for [[Passafire]], [[Ra (American band)|RA]], Adakin, Ryan White and [[Flyleaf (band)|Flyleaf]]. Following the release of their self-titled album \"Lullwater\", the single \"Albatross\" received heavy rotation on [[Octane (Sirius XM)|SiriusXM Radio's Octane Channel]] channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rockallphotography.com/?p=24405|title=Lullwater \u2013 Featured on SirusXM radio Octane Channel|first=Theresa|last=Patrick|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015 \u2013 2016: second album release and new member===\nWhile touring, the band began writing new songs for the next album.  Lullwater chose to record their second album at [[Sonic Ranch]] in El Paso, TX.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crypticrock.com/lullwater-revival-album-review/|title=Lullwater \u2013 Revival (Album Review)|first=Alexis|last=Coleman|date=December 28, 2015}}</ref> The result was \u201cRevival\u201d, a 12-track album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.getitonvinyl.com/lullwater-revival/|title=Album Review: Lullwater \"Revival\"|date=October 14, 2015}}</ref>  After the recording of \u201cRevival\u201d, Daniel Binnie replaced Brett Strickland on lead guitar. Following the release of \u201cRevival\u201d, Lullwater toured for 12 months to support the album, opening for [[Amaranthe]]  , [[Butcher Babies]], Another Lost Year, Temple Agents, [[Theory of a Deadman]] and [[Candlebox]] until the end of 2016.\n\n===2017 \u2013 present:  touring and a third album===\nLullwater continued to tour in 2017, 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shockwavemagazine.com/another-lost-year-announce-tour-with-never-say-die-and-lullwater-promote-new-website/|title=Another Lost Year Announce Tour with Never Say Die and Lullwater; Promote New Website|date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> In December 2017, Lullwater moved into Marigny Studios in New Orleans, LA to record their next album, \u201cVoodoo\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rockallphotography.com/?p=27744|title=Lullwater ready to unleash the magic of Voodoo to the world|first=Shawn|last=Wiseman|date=February 17, 2019}}</ref> Jacob Herrmann from Sweden was the producer/engineer for \u201cVoodoo\u201d along with Justin Davis.  Voodoo was finally released on February 22, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rockdocumented.com/2019/02/08/album-review-lullwater-voodoo/|title=LULLWATER RELEASE VOODOO|date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>  The song Dark Divided off of \"Voodoo\" was listed in The Top 100 Hard Rock Songs of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://hardrockdaddy.com/2020/01/05/top-100-hard-rock-songs-of-2019/|title=Top 100 Hard Rock Songs of 2019|last=AW|date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> I'm Music Magazine included Lullwater's \u201cVoodoo\u201d among their top 28 Albums of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://im-musicmagazine.com/f/28-best-albums-of-2019?fbclid=IwAR0TleZYhLJs0-uzDqdegY1BPhIJN4IYBU3vfKMCkZpVOdz4ituVCDiQVuU|title=Top 28 Best Albums from 2019|website=www.im-musicmagazine.com/}}</ref> Dark Divided from \u201cVoodoo\u201d hit number 4 on the Foundations Secondary Market Rock Chart and made it to the most added at [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Mainstream Rock indicator on October 5, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/rock-songs/2019-10-05 |title=Lullwater's Dark Divided reaches number 4 on Billboards Mainstream Rock Indicator|website=www.billboard.com/|date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Tours to support \u201cVoodoo\u201d followed while opening for Another Lost Year, [[Gin Blossoms]], [[Collective Soul]], [[Candlebox]], Never Say Die, [[Daughtry (band)|Daughtry]], Kirra, Blacktop Mojo,  [[Powerman 5000]], [[Sevendust]] and [[Tremonti (band)|Tremonti]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/sevendust-announces-early-2019-u-s-tour-with-tremonti/|title=SEVENDUST Announces Early 2019 U.S. Tour With TREMONTI; BLABBERMOUTH.NET Presale Available|date=November 12, 2018|website=BLABBERMOUTH.NET}}</ref>  Sapphire Bullets ranked Lullwater's Voodoo album as one of the top 50 albums in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sapphirebulletsofpurelove.blogspot.com/?m=1/|title=Lullwater \u2013 Sapphire Bullet's Top Albums of 2019|first=Luke|last=Dunmore|date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*\u201cLullwater\u201d  (2013)  Released on September 17, 2013\n*\u201cRevival\u201d   (2015)    Released October 23, 2015\n*\u201cVoodoo\u201d   (2019)   Released February 22, 2019\n[[File:Cover of Lullwater, released in 2013.jpg|thumb|Cover of Lullwater, released in 2013]]\n[[File:Revival Cover, released in 2015.jpg|thumb|Revival Cover, released in 2015]]\n[[File:Voodoo Cover, released in 2019.jpg|thumb|Voodoo Cover, released in 2019]]\n\n==Band members==\n'''Current Members'''<br> \n                                                                                                                                                    \n*John Strickland:  Lead vocals and rhythm guitar\n*Joseph Wilson: drums and vocals\n*Roy Beatty: bass and vocals\n*Daniel Binnie:  lead guitar\n\n===Past members===\n*Phil Bush\n*Nick Thomas\n*Brett Strickland\n\n===Instruments===\n*John Strickland:  [[Gibson Les Paul]]\n*Joseph Wilson:  [[Pearl Drums]] / [[Avedis Zildjian Company|Zildjian Cymballs]]\n*Roy Beatty:  [[Dingwall Designer Guitars|Dingwall Guitars]]\n*Daniel Binnie:   [[Gibson Les Paul]]\n\n===Timeline===\n\n{{#tag:timeline\n|ImageSize = width:600 height:auto barincrement:25\nPlotArea   = left:120 bottom:100 top:10 right:10\nAlignbars  = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/01/2007 till:{{#time:d/m/Y}}\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend     = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:1\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:2007\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2007\n\nColors = \n id:vocals   value:red       legend:Lead_vocals\n id:guitar   value:green     legend:Guitar\n id:keys     value:purple    legend:Keyboards\n id:bass     value:blue      legend:Bass_guitar\n id:drums    value:orange    legend:Drums\n id:backing  value:pink      legend:Backing_vocals\n id:perc     value:claret    legend:Percussion\n id:album    value:black     legend:Studio_album\n id:bs value:gray(0.1)\n\nLineData =\n layer:back\n color:album\n at:29/12/2013\n at:11/10/2015\n at:22/02/2019\n\nBarData =\n\n bar:JS text:\"John Strickland\"\n bar:BS text:\"Brett Strickland\"\n bar:PB text:\"Phil Bush\"\n bar:NT text:\"Nick Thomas\"\n bar:RB text:\"Roy Beatty\"\n bar:JW text:\"Joseph Wilson\"\n bar:DB text:\"Daniel Binnie\"\n\nPlotData =\n\n bar:JS from:start till:end color:vocals width:13\n bar:JS from