 its influences in the Seattle [[Grunge]] Sound and 80's hard rock.  Formed by John Strickland (lead vocals, rhythm guitar), Lullwater also includes Roy Beatty (bass), Joseph Wilson (drums) and Daniel Binnie (guitar). The band released their debut album, \u201cLullwater\u201d, on September 17, 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screamermagazine.com/interviews/done-lullwater-athens-georgia-delivers/|title=LULLWATER - Athens, Georgia Delivers Again|date=August 27, 2014|website=Screamer Magazine}}</ref> and toured to support that album.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://betweenthenotes.blog/2014/10/23/interview-with-lullwater/|title=Interview with Lullwater|date=October 23, 2014}}</ref> The band was named from the street that their original drummer lived on in Athens.  Their band practice house was on Lullwater Road in Athens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.last.fm/music/Lullwater|title=Lullwater music, videos, stats, and photos|website=Last.fm}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===2007 \u2013 2011: Early days of the band and lineup changes===\nLullwater is brought together by John Strickland.  He completed the band's lineup by using Brett Strickland on lead guitar.  Drum duties were handled by Nick Thomas.  Phil Bush was the bass player. In 2009, Roy Beatty replaced Phil Bush as Lullwater's bass player.  In 2011, drummer Nick Thomas left the band and was replaced by Joseph Wilson from Savannah, GA, former dummer for Wormsloew.\n\n===2012 \u2013 2014: first album release===\nWith its new lineup, Lullwater began playing more clubs and touring.  In 2013, Lullwater recorded their first album at [[London Bridge Studio]] in Seattle, WA.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  Lullwater's self-titled album \u201cLullwater\u201d, released on September 17, 2013, pays homage to the grunge bands of the early 1990s who influenced their sound. The album was recorded on tape at London Bridge Studios in Seattle, WA and produced by Jonathan Plum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/noisetrade/music/lullwater|title=Lullwater Albums :: NoiseTrade :: Paste Magazine|website=www.pastemagazine.com}}</ref>  To promote \u201cLullwater\u201d, the band toured for 10 months following the release of the album, opening for [[Passafire]], [[Ra (American band)|RA]], Adakin, Ryan White and [[Flyleaf (band)|Flyleaf]]. Following the release of their self-titled album \"Lullwater\", the single \"Albatross\" received heavy rotation on [[Octane (Sirius XM)|SiriusXM Radio's Octane Channel]] channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rockallphotography.com/?p=24405|title=Lullwater \u2013 Featured on SirusXM radio Octane Channel|first=Theresa|last=Patrick|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015 \u2013 2016: second album release and new member===\nWhile touring, the band began writing new songs for the next album.  Lullwater chose to record their second album at [[Sonic Ranch]] in El Paso, TX.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crypticrock.com/lullwater-revival-album-review/|title=Lullwater \u2013 Revival (Album Review)|first=Alexis|last=Coleman|date=December 28, 2015}}</ref> The result was \u201cRevival\u201d, a 12-track album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.getitonvinyl.com/lullwater-revival/|title=Album Review: Lullwater \"Revival\"|date=October 14, 2015}}</ref>  After the recording of \u201cRevival\u201d, Daniel Binnie replaced Brett Strickland on lead guitar. Following the release of \u201cRevival\u201d, Lullwater toured for 12 months to support the album, opening for [[Amaranthe]]  , [[Butcher Babies]], Another Lost Year, Temple Agents, [[Theory of a Deadman]] and [[Candlebox]] until the end of 2016.\n\n===2017 \u2013 present:  touring and a third album===\nLullwater continued to tour in 2017, 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shockwavemagazine.com/another-lost-year-announce-tour-with-never-say-die-and-lullwater-promote-new-website/|title=Another Lost Year Announce Tour with Never Say Die and Lullwater; Promote New Website|date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> In December 2017, Lullwater moved into Marigny Studios in New Orleans, LA to record their next album, \u201cVoodoo\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rockallphotography.com/?p=27744|title=Lullwater ready to unleash the magic of Voodoo to the world|first=Shawn|last=Wiseman|date=February 17, 2019}}</ref> Jacob Herrmann from Sweden was the producer/engineer for \u201cVoodoo\u201d along with Justin Davis.  Voodoo was finally released on February 22, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rockdocumented.com/2019/02/08/album-review-lullwater-voodoo/|title=LULLWATER RELEASE VOODOO|date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>  The song Dark Divided off of \"Voodoo\" was listed in The Top 100 Hard Rock Songs of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://hardrockdaddy.com/2020/01/05/top-100-hard-rock-songs-of-2019/|title=Top 100 Hard Rock Songs of 2019|last=AW|date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> I'm Music Magazine included Lullwater's \u201cVoodoo\u201d among their top 28 Albums of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://im-musicmagazine.com/f/28-best-albums-of-2019?fbclid=IwAR0TleZYhLJs0-uzDqdegY1BPhIJN4IYBU3vfKMCkZpVOdz4ituVCDiQVuU|title=Top 28 Best Albums from 2019|website=www.im-musicmagazine.com/}}</ref> Dark Divided from \u201cVoodoo\u201d hit number 4 on the Foundations Secondary Market Rock Chart and made it to the most added at [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Mainstream Rock indicator on October 5, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/rock-songs/2019-10-05 |title=Lullwater's Dark Divided reaches number 4 on Billboards Mainstream Rock Indicator|website=www.billboard.com/|date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Tours to support \u201cVoodoo\u201d followed while opening for Another Lost Year, [[Gin Blossoms]], [[Collective Soul]], [[Candlebox]], Never Say Die, [[Daughtry (band)|Daughtry]], Kirra, Blacktop Mojo,  [[Powerman 5000]], [[Sevendust]] and [[Tremonti (band)|Tremonti]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/sevendust-announces-early-2019-u-s-tour-with-tremonti/|title=SEVENDUST Announces Early 2019 U.S. Tour With TREMONTI; BLABBERMOUTH.NET Presale Available|date=November 12, 2018|website=BLABBERMOUTH.NET}}</ref>  Sapphire Bullets ranked Lullwater's Voodoo album as one of the top 50 albums in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sapphirebulletsofpurelove.blogspot.com/?m=1/|title=Lullwater \u2013 Sapphire Bullet's Top Albums of 2019|first=Luke|last=Dunmore|date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*\u201cLullwater\u201d  (2013)  Released on September 17, 2013\n*\u201cRevival\u201d   (2015)    Released October 23, 2015\n*\u201cVoodoo\u201d   (2019)   Released February 22, 2019\n[[File:Cover of Lullwater, released in 2013.jpg|thumb|Cover of Lullwater, released in 2013]]\n[[File:Revival Cover, released in 2015.jpg|thumb|Revival Cover, released in 2015]]\n[[File:Voodoo Cover, released in 2019.jpg|thumb|Voodoo Cover, released in 2019]]\n\n==Band members==\n'''Current Members'''<br> \n                                                                                                                                                    \n*John Strickland:  Lead vocals and rhythm guitar\n*Joseph Wilson: drums and vocals\n*Roy Beatty: bass and vocals\n*Daniel Binnie:  lead guitar\n\n===Past members===\n*Phil Bush\n*Nick Thomas\n*Brett Strickland\n\n===Instruments===\n*John Strickland:  [[Gibson Les Paul]]\n*Joseph Wilson:  [[Pearl Drums]] / [[Avedis Zildjian Company|Zildjian Cymballs]]\n*Roy Beatty:  [[Dingwall Designer Guitars|Dingwall Guitars]]\n*Daniel Binnie:   [[Gibson Les Paul]]\n\n===Timeline===\n\n{{#tag:timeline\n|ImageSize = width:600 height:auto barincrement:25\nPlotArea   = left:120 bottom:100 top:10 right:10\nAlignbars  = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/01/2007 till:{{#time:d/m/Y}}\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend     = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:1\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:2007\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2007\n\nColors = \n id:vocals   value:red       legend:Lead_vocals\n id:guitar   value:green     legend:Guitar\n id:keys     value:purple    legend:Keyboards\n id:bass     value:blue      legend:Bass_guitar\n id:drums    value:orange    legend:Drums\n id:backing  value:pink      legend:Backing_vocals\n id:perc     value:claret    legend:Percussion\n id:album    value:black     legend:Studio_album\n id:bs value:gray(0.1)\n\nLineData =\n layer:back\n color:album\n at:29/12/2013\n at:11/10/2015\n at:22/02/2019\n\nBarData =\n\n bar:JS text:\"John Strickland\"\n bar:BS text:\"Brett Strickland\"\n bar:PB text:\"Phil Bush\"\n bar:NT text:\"Nick Thomas\"\n bar:RB text:\"Roy Beatty\"\n bar:JW text:\"Joseph Wilson\"\n bar:DB text:\"Daniel Binnie\"\n\nPlotData =\n\n bar:JS from:start till:end color:vocals width:13\n bar:JS from:start till:end color:guitar width:3\n\n bar:BS from:start till:22/07/2016 color:guitar width:13\n\n bar:PB from:start till:01/01/2009 color:bass width:13\n\n bar:NT from:start till:01/01/2011 color:drums width:13\n\n bar:RB from:01/01/2009 till:end color:bass width:13\n bar:RB from:01/01/2009 till:end color:backing width:3\n\n bar:JW from:01/01/2011 till:end color:perc width:13\n bar:JW from:01/01/2011 till:end color:drums width:8\n bar:JW from:01/01/2011 till:end color:backing width:3\n\n bar:DB from:22/07/2016 till:end color:guitar width:13\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Category:Grunge musical groups]]\n[[Category:American post-grunge musical groups]]\n[[Category:Rock music groups from Georgia (U.S. state]]\n", "name_user": "Lullwaterfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "working on category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lullwater_(band)"}
{"title_page": "1922 Winslow Junction train derailment", "text_new": "The '''1922 Winslow Junction train derailment''' was a July 2, 1922{{sfn|Cook|Coxey|1980|page=172}} accident on [[Atlantic City Railroad]]'s Camden to Atlantic City route. Train \u2116 33 the Owl going {{convert|90|mi}} per hour sped through an open switch at [[Winslow Township, New Jersey|Winslow Junction]]. 7 were killed, 89 were injured.{{sfn|Gladulich|1986}}\n\n==Accident==\nOn [[Atlantic City Railroad]]'s Camden to Atlantic City Line, in Winslow, New Jersey: at Winslow Junction near the WA Tower, On July 2, 1922, shortly before 11:30pm,{{sfn|Gladulich|1986}} a derailment of train \u2116 33 the Owl, with Philadelphia and Reading Railway Eng \u2116 349. The train was going approximately {{convert|90|mi}} per hour as it sped through an open switch.{{sfn|Gladulich|1986}} The derailment of train \u2116 33 resulted in most of the six-car Atlantic City express plunging down an embankment into the WJ&S's southbound Cape May branch connecting track. This resulted in the death of 3 passengers, 3 employees and 1 Pullman porter, and the injury of 84 passengers and 5 employees.<ref name=\"ICC report WJTD\">{{cite web |title = ICC report on Winslow Junction Train Derailment |work = Railway Signal Engineer |publisher = Simmons Boardman Publishing Co (Chicago)|pages = 387\u2013389|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=yRI4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA389|year=1922}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nThe [[Interstate Commerce Commission]] investigation found that the route could have been changed after the train had passed the distant signal at the plant was not interlocked, but there was not evidence that this had been done. The report further stated that the engineer failed to acknowledge the junction by blowing the whistle and attempt to stop the train.{{sfn|Gladulich|1986}}\n\n===From the ICC report===\n\"This accident was caused by failure of Engineman Wescott of train \u2116 33 to be governed by automatic and interlocking signal indications, which resulted in train \u2116 33 taking the diverging route at a high rate of speed and being derailed due to the outer rail of the curve giving way.\"<ref name=\"ICC report WJTD\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Atlantic City Railroad]]\n*[[Reading Company]]\n*[[Pennsylvania\u2013Reading Seashore Lines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book \n|title= Atlantic City Railroad: The Royal Route To The Sea\n|first1= W. George |last1=Cook |first2=William J. |last2=Coxey\n|year= 1980 \n|publisher= West Jersey Chapter, National Railway Historical Society \n|location= [[Palmyra, New Jersey]]\n|pages= 123\u2013124\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book \n| last= Gladulich \n| first= Richard M. \n| title=By rail to the boardwalk \n| year=1986 \n| publisher=Trans Anglo Books \n| location=[[Glendale, California]] \n| isbn=0-87046-076-5 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19220703&id=zYYwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=x9wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5918,225371&hl=en Eight Killed in Midnight Wreck in New Jersey (The Deseret News, 3 Jul 1922, page 1)]\n*[http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MT19220703.2.6 Many Killed and Injured in Big Wreck (Madera Tribune, 3 Jul 1922, page 1)]\n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/6957160// Nine Meet Death, 32 Injured, In Wreck of Jersey Flyer (Franklin News-Herald, 3 Jul 1922, page 1)]\n*[http://badahistory.net/view.php?ID=66 Theodore M Selden (African-Americans at Dartmouth College)]\n\n{{1922 railway accidents}}\n{{coord|39.7199|-74.9053|type:event_globe:earth_region:US-NJ|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winslow Junction Train Derailment}}\n[[Category:Railway accidents and incidents in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving Atlantic City Railroad]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania-Reading Seashore Lines]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents in 1922]]\n[[Category:1922 in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Winslow Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Derailments in the United States]]\n[[Category:July 1922 events]]\n\n\n{{US-rail-transport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''1922 Winslow Junction train derailment''' was a July 2, 1922{{sfn|Cook|Coxey|1980|page=172}} accident on [[Atlantic City Railroad]]'s Camden to Atlantic City route. Train \u2116 33 the Owl going {{convert|90|mi}} per hour sped through an open switch at [[Winslow Township, New Jersey|Winslow Junction]]. 7 were killed, 89 were injured.{{sfn|Gladulich|1986}}\n\n==Accident==\nOn [[Atlantic City Railroad]]'s Camden to Atlantic City Line, in Winslow, New Jersey: at Winslow Junction near the WA Tower, On July 2, 1922, shortly before 11:30pm,{{sfn|Gladulich|1986}} a derailment of train \u2116 33 the Owl, with Philadelphia and Reading Railway Eng \u2116 349. The train was going approximately {{convert|90|mi}} per hour as it sped through an open switch.{{sfn|Gladulich|1986}} The derailment of train \u2116 33 resulted in most of the six-car Atlantic City express plunging down an embankment into the WJ&S's southbound Cape May branch connecting track. This resulted in the death of 3 passengers, 3 employees and 1 Pullman porter, and the injury of 84 passengers and 5 employees.<ref name=\"ICC report WJTD\">{{cite web |title = ICC report on Winslow Junction Train Derailment |work = Railway Signal Engineer |publisher = Simmons Boardman Publishing Co (Chicago)|pages = 387\u2013389|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=yRI4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA389&dq=%22taking+the+diverging+route+at+a+high+rate+of+speed+and+being+derailed%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiok4_gyM7PAhWBHD4KHZcUCA8Q6AEIHjAA#v=onepage&q=%22taking%20the%20diverging%20route%20at%20a%20high%20rate%20of%20speed%20and%20being%20derailed%22&f=false|accessdate = 2016-10-09}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nThe [[Interstate Commerce Commission]] investigation found that the route could have been changed after the train had passed the distant signal at the plant was not interlocked, but there was not evidence that this had been done. The report further stated that the engineer failed to acknowledge the junction by blowing the whistle and attempt to stop the train.{{sfn|Gladulich|1986}}\n\n===From the ICC report===\n\"This accident was caused by failure of Engineman Wescott of train \u2116 33 to be governed by automatic and interlocking signal indications, which resulted in train \u2116 33 taking the diverging route at a high rate of speed and being derailed due to the outer rail of the curve giving way.\"<ref name=\"ICC report WJTD\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Atlantic City Railroad]]\n*[[Reading Company]]\n*[[Pennsylvania\u2013Reading Seashore Lines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book \n|title= Atlantic City Railroad: The Royal Route To The Sea\n|first1= W. George |last1=Cook |first2=William J. |last2=Coxey\n|year= 1980 \n|publisher= West Jersey Chapter, National Railway Historical Society \n|location= [[Palmyra, New Jersey]]\n|pages= 123\u2013124\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book \n| last= Gladulich \n| first= Richard M. \n| authorlink=  \n| title=By rail to the boardwalk \n| year=1986 \n| publisher=Trans Anglo Books \n| location=[[Glendale, California]] \n| isbn=0-87046-076-5 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19220703&id=zYYwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=x9wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5918,225371&hl=en Eight Killed in Midnight Wreck in New Jersey (The Deseret News, 3 Jul 1922, page 1)]\n*[http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MT19220703.2.6 Many Killed and Injured in Big Wreck (Madera Tribune, 3 Jul 1922, page 1)]\n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/6957160// Nine Meet Death, 32 Injured, In Wreck of Jersey Flyer (Franklin News-Herald, 3 Jul 1922, page 1)]\n*[http://badahistory.net/view.php?ID=66 Theodore M Selden (African-Americans at Dartmouth College)]\n\n{{1922 railway accidents}}\n{{coord|39.7199|-74.9053|type:event_globe:earth_region:US-NJ|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winslow Junction Train Derailment}}\n[[Category:Railway accidents and incidents in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving Atlantic City Railroad]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania-Reading Seashore Lines]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents in 1922]]\n[[Category:1922 in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Winslow Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Derailments in the United States]]\n[[Category:July 1922 events]]\n\n\n{{US-rail-transport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "Script-assisted fixes: perCS1andMOS:ITALICS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1922_Winslow_Junction_train_derailment"}
